Title: OVERLORD (2018)- Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment: Just a quick critical review and i know im late to review it. Before i watched this movie at a discount theatre i have not heard of this movie. I didnt watch any trailers prior to seeing it but judging by the title i assumed it was about ww2. When the movie started it was a full on ww2 experience. The planes, flack, the static line jump, and the normandy landing was grade A ww2 filmmaking. And i didnt discover the twist from ww2 to fiction until the "van helsing village scene." I think we all secretly wanted a nazi zombies movie and i wasnt dissapointed. Overall a 9/10 movie. Now the only thing (i know people have said it dosent matter) was the black soldier. I 100% agree, It really dosent matter since it is fiction. However, my initial reaction to the ww2 setting in the beginning was outstanding and when the camera showed a black dude in a stick of all white dudes my reaction was like more than confused and i think this is because i was expecting an immersive ww2 film judging from the first opening scene, but the main issue is that i also  thought this film was going to break that trend in todays media on forced diversity since it was going to be about ww2. Obviously i knew right away it was fiction after the opening scene so i didnt care if the dude was black. Diversity is good and should be an important part in any movie but you can tell that if they didnt include at least one diverse character then it would be considered "racist." I loved the movie but, feel free to disagree with me, i believe that forced diversity, political agendas, or political stances needs to be removed or banned from all entertainment. There are many examples of forced diversity in a lot of movies and video games and this needs to stop.

Title: OVERLORD (2018)- Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Think this is a good movie (good plot, acting, and general production) but feel its also unnecessarily ruined by being too blatantly PC. Its not a train-smash but I think its sad that the such a well made movie is "diminished" for such a reason.
I've resigned myself to expect a bit of PC in every movie (and series) that comes out these days, though it would be nice if they could be a bit more subtle (and realistic) about it.  

The argument that "its just a zombie/fantasy movie, so who cares?" is really not good enough here. The basic purpose of any fantasy movie is to "immerse" the audience in the fantasy world and make it "believable" up to point where you don't really notice the "fantasy/falsehood", ie. you're "sucked in". So, obviously zombies are fantasy creatures but "unrealistic zombies" are also immersion-breaking. In this case, the zombies were done well, however, making movies (or series, or anything) based in historical times (whether it includes a fantasy element of zombies, robot dinosaurs, or rainbow unicorns, etc), where a general standard of realism is upheld EXCEPT when it comes to racism and racial segregation, which, for some weird unexplained reason, doesn't exist, or is ignored, or altered into contrived unrealistic scenarios, is also just really strange and immersion-breaking. 

Because its "noticeable" (and in my opinion "suspicious"), and it instantly pops the spell-binding bubble of fantasy that movie had been weaving up till then. In this movie its right from he beginning.
Its not that I didn't like Adepo's (and Woodbine's) performances. I thought they were great. Within the story I just thought their positions and relationships with the other soldiers "within the context of the era in which it was set" was noticeably contrived, and it set an unnecessary "unrealistic tone" to the movie right from the start. 
I just feel its all silly and unnecessary, and its kind of ruining  movies (and series) in general these days.

To make matters worst, the reanimated soldiers have enhanced regeneration ability so killing them with knives and bullets is very difficult.  However, flame throwers are more effect! If someone is a fan of zombie and war films, they will find this one worth viewing, imo.

Title: OVERLORD (2018)- Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
There's always this tendency for supernatural movies with a historical setting, or any setting that many people take seriously, that will always end up in disaster. Not many people can pull that kind of thing off. 


In my complete, unbiased opinion, Overlord does an exceptional job at putting together supernatural elements in the historical setting. It's strange to think about it. You know this isn't non-fictional, and you know it couldn't have happened, yet it feels so much like a classic WW2 movie..


There is a nice balance between the main characters coming into conflict with both the infected zombies and human German soldiers, which adds for a very nice mixture. Like rum and coke :)


If you're looking for the more charming aspect of WW2, then you won't be disappointed. The film fits the setting very well. For example, there is one scene where an Allied soldier is using an MG-42, and his friend next to him tells him to hurry up when he reloads. The soldier using the machine gun then responds unpleasantly, "It's a two person gun you idiot!" I know it isn't a huge example, but the fact of the matter still stands. There is accurate usage of weaponry for the most part with excellent sound design.  


I would give it a solid 8/10 which is surprising for a movie that is literally nicknamed "Nazi Zombies"

This battalion did not serve as combat paratroopers, but instead fought the Japanese in a different way. The Japanese were sending thousands of balloon bombs towards the U.S. Northwest. Comment:
Ah! Alright, my nerd rage movie junkie 2 cents in 3, 2, 1,
I fuckin love zombies. As a plot device and literary/cinematic tool and as a character and representation and as a monster.
They say monsters are a commentary on how man views itself. It's like a projection of his/her fears. 
The concept of zombie combined with the grunt work of soldier and military is GENIUS!!
The concept of being mindless, taking orders, being primal...being....expendable üò¢
So many forgotten names...
Missions buried.
The push for military technology so perverse that it even dabbles in black magic, ancient text and the unthinkable. Anything to win. The mindset of warfare...but...at What cost? 
How much war until there is nothing left and we already lost what we were fighting for in the first place. Our humanity.

OVERLORD
noun
a person who is lord over another or over other lords:
to obey the will of one's sovereign and overlord.
a person of great influence, authority, power, or the like:
the overlords of industry.

Title: OVERLORD (2018)- Official Trailer - Paramount Pictures
Comment:
Footnote: I come from a family of afro-american vets, and great-gran-daddy fought the Nazis in World War II in an all  black segregated unit. So i'm a big military history guy and i've been with my family to alot of veterans associations and parades, etc. (before a dumbass makes a racist comment about blacks despite them fighting for the country kicking ass in many wars up through today)

Now. With that said: *WHY IS THIS AN INTEGRATED UNIT IN WORLD WAR II?!?!?* LOL. This isn't debateable, there's no other 'opinions'. "It's 100% flat historical fact that the military was de facto segregated*. Hollywood isn't dumb enough not to know this as they've made dozens of World War II movies for decades including those that ACKNOWLEDGE THIS LOL. I just don't get why the hell they couldn't even bother with this fact just out of desperation to have a 'black protagonist'. They could've easily done this and had two units stranded in one location, one black one white--which would've made a good paranoia scenario once you throw zombies in the mix--thus gotten what you wnated, had a black soldier character shooting guns, explosions, CGI, FX, gore, etc lol everything that they had in this trailer. Don't get me wrong, despite that this is obviously a rip off of Frankenstein's Monsters, Wolfenstein and Call of Duty: Zombies DLC I still love to be entertained by this movie. The concept is fun and looks badass. I just hate how they totally fucked up with THAT historical accuracy which was so in your face and OBVIOUS during the 40's!

I mean is there an explanation for why the guy is even flying in with other soldiers? It's not even acknowledged ore explained lol. It's just "oh hey....time to go on a special mission". I'm of the school where I hate hyper-PC crap, I feel having a genuinely written story and role for minority characters is better than ignoring history just to shoe-horn someone in to be a Token. But Hollywood is too damn politically correct to do that, since that would require *originality*.
